You've already given me,

260
00:20:13,520 --> 00:20:15,390
like, 200 quid.

261
00:20:15,440 --> 00:20:17,750
She gave me ten grand for you.

262
00:20:17,800 --> 00:20:19,200
Take it.

263
00:20:20,400 --> 00:20:23,070
You could go somewhere with it.

264
00:20:23,680 --> 00:20:26,880
- I don't have a passport.
- Well, get one.

265
00:20:27,440 --> 00:20:29,380
Travel. Go abroad.

266
00:20:33,720 --> 00:20:36,270
No. You're all right.

267
00:20:36,320 --> 00:20:38,630
- I don't want it.
- Why did she want me to look after you?

268
00:20:38,680 --> 00:20:41,680
I don't know what she wanted me to do.

269
00:20:42,280 --> 00:20:44,750
How am I meant to help you?

270
00:20:46,680 --> 00:20:48,620
Tell me, Frankie.

271
00:20:52,240 --> 00:20:55,040
I can't sleep in the flat no more.

272
00:20:55,360 --> 00:20:58,460
I can't sleep at home. I can't sleep...

273
00:20:59,200 --> 00:21:00,790
.. anywhere.

274
00:21:00,840 --> 00:21:04,350
I walk around all night, until it's light,

275
00:21:04,400 --> 00:21:07,500
and then I go to work... and I go home.

276
00:21:09,080 --> 00:21:10,840
And, uh...

277
00:21:12,520 --> 00:21:15,680
Yeah, I'm, uh... I'm drowning.

278
00:21:25,080 --> 00:21:27,480
Come on. Come on, Frankie.

279
00:21:41,360 --> 00:21:44,030
- Last one in is...
- Chicken!

280
00:22:11,280 --> 00:22:12,800
Whoo!

281
00:22:55,960 --> 00:22:58,160
Will your mother be up?

282
00:23:00,480 --> 00:23:02,600
Yeah. Looks like it.

283
00:23:07,920 --> 00:23:10,120
I knew you'd come home.

284
00:23:12,320 --> 00:23:15,060
The colour's drained out of you.

285
00:23:19,800 --> 00:23:23,470
- Thank you. - I heard you
searched Michael's place?

286
00:23:23,520 --> 00:23:24,990
Yeah.

287
00:23:25,040 --> 00:23:26,510
What did you do that for?

288
00:23:26,560 --> 00:23:29,560
Just a part of the ongoing investigation.

289
00:23:30,400 --> 00:23:32,550
Oh.

290
00:23:32,600 --> 00:23:34,990
Right. Do yous want some toast?

291
00:23:35,040 --> 00:23:36,440
No.

292
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:42,110
- How old were you there?
- Oh, about...

293
00:23:42,160 --> 00:23:43,910
about a month.

294
00:23:43,960 --> 00:23:45,110
You were born in Cork?

295
00:23:45,160 --> 00:23:48,960
Me waters broke when we
were staying at me sister's.

296
00:23:53,400 --> 00:23:54,790
And that's you as well?

297
00:23:54,840 --> 00:23:56,780
Our late surprise.

298
00:24:00,760 --> 00:24:04,320
Frankie. Upstairs and get a dry shirt on.

299
00:24:07,040 --> 00:24:08,480
Do it.

300
00:24:21,160 --> 00:24:23,910
He's got some idea about her flat.

301
00:24:23,960 --> 00:24:25,870
Told him we need to sell it.

302
00:24:25,920 --> 00:24:28,310
You can do something with money.

303
00:24:28,360 --> 00:24:31,270
Not bricks and mortar...
and a pasta machine.

304
00:24:31,320 --> 00:24:33,950
Oh, a pasta machine?

305
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:37,110
You ever known our Stevie make
a bowl of food in her life?

306
00:24:37,160 --> 00:24:39,550
She made good scrambled eggs.

307
00:24:39,600 --> 00:24:42,800
And she could laugh
till she pissed herself.

308
00:24:43,320 --> 00:24:46,280
She was loyal, passionate and true.

309
00:24:48,320 --> 00:24:50,310
And she loved.

310
00:24:50,360 --> 00:24:54,070
But the one person she loved
with everything was that boy.

311
00:24:54,120 --> 00:24:57,120
Why did she love that boy so much, Bridie?

312
00:25:01,640 --> 00:25:03,160
Hello?

313
00:25:06,600 --> 00:25:08,800
Yeah. Yep, I've heard.

314
00:25:10,320 --> 00:25:12,470
I know.

315
00:25:12,520 --> 00:25:15,320
No. Not now, it's not a good time.

316
00:25:16,080 --> 00:25:18,150
Yeah.

317
00:25:18,200 --> 00:25:20,470
OK.

318
00:25:20,520 --> 00:25:21,720
Yes.

319
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:27,110
'I don't know why you've
brought me here, John.

320
00:25:27,160 --> 00:25:28,720
'Why? Hm?'

321
00:25:40,520 --> 00:25:42,720
'Put him down, Stevie.

322
00:25:45,560 --> 00:25:47,560
'Put your boy down!

323
00:25:51,040 --> 00:25:52,550
'Frankie.

324
00:25:52,600 --> 00:25:55,510
'Come on! Come here!'

325
00:25:55,560 --> 00:25:58,310
How do you turn that thing off?

326
00:26:02,160 --> 00:26:03,830
Turn it off.

327
00:26:07,480 --> 00:26:09,950
- SIT DOWN!
- Turn it off!

328
00:26:18,280 --> 00:26:20,750
What else are you prepared to lie about?

329
00:26:20,800 --> 00:26:22,470
E6 Holdings.

330
00:26:23,800 --> 00:26:25,990
Do you know the company?

331
00:26:26,040 --> 00:26:27,640
No comment.

332
00:26:30,280 --> 00:26:33,320
He takes care of you, Michael.
Takes care of you well.

333
00:26:34,520 --> 00:26:36,790
He's been a good friend.

334
00:26:38,400 --> 00:26:41,390
The last thing Stevie asked me to do,

335
00:26:41,440 --> 00:26:44,510
before she died, was
to take care of Frankie.

336
00:26:44,560 --> 00:26:45,960
Her son.

337
00:26:48,320 --> 00:26:50,190
I want a lawyer.

338
00:26:51,240 --> 00:26:53,180
You can have one.

339
00:26:55,520 --> 00:26:58,120
This is just the warm-up chat.

340
00:27:04,040 --> 00:27:06,040
Who was the father?

341
00:27:08,280 --> 00:27:09,950
I didn't ask.

342
00:27:10,720 --> 00:27:13,830
Probably a poke for a pound
round the back of Greens.

343
00:27:13,880 --> 00:27:16,310
She opened her legs for everyone.

344
00:27:16,360 --> 00:27:17,960
Cheap date.

345
00:27:20,960 --> 00:27:23,500
She wanted to flush him away.

346
00:27:24,320 --> 00:27:26,920
Wanted to flush that boy away.

347
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:30,070
I took him in.

348
00:27:30,120 --> 00:27:31,950
I made him my own.

349
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:34,470
Kept him on the straight.

350
00:27:34,520 --> 00:27:37,150
Until you let him work for Michael.

351
00:27:37,200 --> 00:27:38,990
Oh, he's a big boy.

352
00:27:39,040 --> 00:27:41,350
Is that why she went in to investigate?

353
00:27:41,400 --> 00:27:43,400
To protect Frankie?

354
00:27:44,800 --> 00:27:46,400
No comment.

355
00:27:47,920 --> 00:27:51,480
The night Stevie was murdered,
the car she was shot from...

356
00:27:53,080 --> 00:27:56,580
.. was left at a scrapyard.
It's a blue Mondeo.

357
00:27:58,880 --> 00:28:01,280
Do you recognise this car?

358
00:28:04,880 --> 00:28:06,710
- No?
- No. No.

359
00:28:06,760 --> 00:28:09,230
But you know who dumped it.

360
00:28:10,600 --> 00:28:12,800
You dumped it, Bridie.

361
00:28:14,360 --> 00:28:17,150
A figure wearing that coat...

362
00:28:17,200 --> 00:28:19,630
was seen ditching it at a scrapyard,

363
00:28:19,680 --> 00:28:21,790
90 minutes after she was shot.

364
00:28:21,840 --> 00:28:24,870
Five foot seven, five foot eight.

365
00:28:24,920 --> 00:28:27,320
About your height, Bridie.

366
00:28:31,440 --> 00:28:33,470
Oh, is it March?

367
00:28:33,520 --> 00:28:37,430
When the mad hares
breed? Because you're mad!

368
00:28:40,920 --> 00:28:44,240
Madness can bring its own
kind of clarity, Bridie.

369
00:28:45,880 --> 00:28:48,620
Did you shoot your own daughter?

370
00:28:55,040 --> 00:28:57,180
Did Michael kill her?

371
00:28:58,480 --> 00:29:00,750
Did Michael kill Stevie?

372
00:29:02,080 --> 00:29:03,680
No comment.

373
00:29:19,600 --> 00:29:21,950
Is that the cleaned-up files?

374
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:23,270
Yeah.

375
00:29:35,080 --> 00:29:36,950
Found something?

376
00:29:38,200 --> 00:29:39,600
Wait...

377
00:30:16,320 --> 00:30:17,990
Easy, Tonto.

378
00:30:36,240 --> 00:30:37,670
The one thing,

379
00:30:37,720 --> 00:30:40,710
the one thing you asked was
that they keep Frankie out of it.

380
00:30:40,760 --> 00:30:43,830
- But they didn't, did they?
- River. Please.

381
00:30:43,880 --> 00:30:46,480
I'm doing this for Frankie.

382
00:30:54,760 --> 00:30:57,390
Some find them a little macabre...

383
00:30:57,440 --> 00:30:59,270
but I like them.

384
00:30:59,320 --> 00:31:03,390
You know, slavery existed even
before the Roman Occupation,

385
00:31:03,440 --> 00:31:06,230
although the true pioneers
of the English slave trade

386
00:31:06,280 --> 00:31:09,360
didn't really kick in
until the mid-16th century.

387
00:31:11,600 --> 00:31:13,870
When Eric and I first
arrived in England, it was,

388
00:31:13,920 --> 00:31:17,830
"No Irish, no coloureds,"
when you tried to rent a room.

389
00:31:17,880 --> 00:31:21,480
You had to fight to get
anywhere in this country.

390
00:31:22,680 --> 00:31:25,350
So, I like to think that, uh...

391
00:31:27,160 --> 00:31:30,990
.. I'm doing my bit for the
next generation coming in.

392
00:31:31,040 --> 00:31:33,510
I'll say the same in court.

393
00:31:35,040 --> 00:31:37,430
I was looking at some
CCTV from that night.

394
00:31:37,480 --> 00:31:41,470
You were right -- we did
have that car out the back.

395
00:31:41,520 --> 00:31:44,190
Everything is digital now, huh?

396
00:31:48,360 --> 00:31:50,910
You paid to have Haider killed.

397
00:31:50,960 --> 00:31:53,700
Did you do the same with Stevie?

398
00:31:54,800 --> 00:31:56,550
You see, that's my point.

399
00:31:56,600 --> 00:32:00,100
You can never underestimate
the power of family.

400
00:32:00,640 --> 00:32:02,550
Stevie never really understood that.

401
00:32:02,600 --> 00:32:05,400
She always put truth before blood.

402
00:32:05,920 --> 00:32:08,670
She was throwing around the threats.

403
00:32:08,720 --> 00:32:11,190
Bridie and Jimmy and Frankie were upset.

404
00:32:11,240 --> 00:32:12,750
I mean, I was willing to let it pass.

405
00:32:12,800 --> 00:32:15,470
I mean, that girl was like a...

406
00:32:17,280 --> 00:32:20,020
I loved her... more than my own.

407
00:32:21,280 --> 00:32:23,870
Yeah, Stevie had a fight with Bridie,

408
00:32:23,920 --> 00:32:26,350
threatened to tell Frankie the truth.

409
00:32:26,400 --> 00:32:29,150
When the truth is, the only
mother who will protect him now

410
00:32:29,200 --> 00:32:30,590
is the one who brought him up.

411
00:32:30,640 --> 00:32:34,520
It would have devastated Frankie
to know who his mother really was.

412
00:32:36,160 --> 00:32:39,160
That's why someone... had to stop her.

413
00:32:56,600 --> 00:33:00,190
He didn't need much persuading.
He was in a terrible way!

414
00:33:00,240 --> 00:33:02,230
He'd been on the lash with Jimmy.

415
00:33:02,280 --> 00:33:04,590
He failed to get it up
with some little tart

416
00:33:04,640 --> 00:33:07,840
that Jimmy found for
him. Came crying to me.

417
00:33:08,840 --> 00:33:12,990
Frankie came to realise the error
of his ways... in confiding in her.

418
00:33:13,040 --> 00:33:16,040
He knew the damage that she could do.

419
00:33:17,400 --> 00:33:20,670
He told me that Stevie
was going to her boss.

420
00:33:20,720 --> 00:33:23,920
He told Stevie things about my business.

421
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:28,000
Things he really shouldn't have said.

422
00:33:29,360 --> 00:33:32,750
Now, I knew that the truth would
come out -- the whole truth --

423
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:35,840
the good and the bad. I
couldn't let Frankie know that.

424
00:33:37,920 --> 00:33:40,110
It's a terrible thing to know,

425
00:33:40,160 --> 00:33:42,830
that you were destined for a toilet pan.

426
00:33:42,880 --> 00:33:46,790
Because there is nothing more
precious than human life.

427
00:33:46,840 --> 00:33:49,840
A lesson, sadly, Stevie learned too late.

428
00:33:51,280 --> 00:33:53,110
Ha-ha!

429
00:33:53,160 --> 00:33:55,070
That's my Monica's girls!

430
00:33:55,120 --> 00:33:56,260
Ah!

431
00:34:00,400 --> 00:34:02,400
Who was the father?

432
00:34:11,480 --> 00:34:13,120
Christ...

433
00:34:15,400 --> 00:34:17,000
She was 14.

434
00:34:19,240 --> 00:34:20,830
You're a monster.

435
00:34:20,880 --> 00:34:22,830
Monsters are for children.

436
00:34:22,880 --> 00:34:25,220
We're all grown-ups here.

437
00:34:26,080 --> 00:34:28,150
I'd hoped employing Tom Read

438
00:34:28,200 --> 00:34:31,990
might have provided a few insurances,

439
00:34:32,040 --> 00:34:34,640
but in the absence of those...

440
00:34:35,640 --> 00:34:38,310
Do you really want
Frankie to know the truth?

441
00:34:38,360 --> 00:34:40,230
The whole truth?

442
00:34:41,800 --> 00:34:44,510
That boy won't come back from that.

443
00:34:44,560 --> 00:34:46,430
Prison?

444
00:34:46,480 --> 00:34:49,080
It would break Stevie's heart.

445
00:34:49,880 --> 00:34:53,400
I will leave it... in your hands.

446
00:35:03,400 --> 00:35:06,950
We went for a drink, I
got pissed too quick.

447
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:09,390
We went home and we... we watched TV.

448
00:35:09,440 --> 00:35:11,030
Frankie, you're lying.

449
00:35:11,080 --> 00:35:12,390
You saying I'm lying?

450
00:35:12,440 --> 00:35:14,230
No, Bridie, I'm saying he's your son...

451
00:35:14,280 --> 00:35:15,710
The person to fear the most is...

452
00:35:15,760 --> 00:35:17,190
.. and a mother protects her son.

453
00:35:17,240 --> 00:35:19,470
.. the one to whom you
gave all your trust.

454
00:35:19,520 --> 00:35:21,830
If only you had replied
to Stevie's question.

455
00:35:21,880 --> 00:35:23,430
We talk, she crosses the road...

456
00:35:23,480 --> 00:35:25,270
If only you had taken her in your arms...

457
00:35:25,320 --> 00:35:28,110
.. she turns her head... and
there's a look of recognition.

458
00:35:28,160 --> 00:35:30,990
- If only. - She knew something
was coming. - If only.

459
00:35:31,040 --> 00:35:33,240
If only.

460
00:35:41,320 --> 00:35:44,230
You want to know who needs
protecting? Frankie.

461
00:35:44,280 --> 00:35:45,670
Do you blame yourself?

462
00:35:45,720 --> 00:35:48,110
I should have sensed something was wrong.

463
00:35:48,160 --> 00:35:52,080
I ignored it, River, I did, I
ignored it, and you did, too.

464
00:35:53,880 --> 00:35:56,280
You don't know what to do.

465
00:36:22,520 --> 00:36:23,860
Sorry.

466
00:36:25,640 --> 00:36:26,990
Sorry.

467
00:36:27,040 --> 00:36:28,990
You're late.

468
00:36:29,040 --> 00:36:31,240
I am indeed late, yeah.

469
00:36:36,680 --> 00:36:40,320
Ask me why I bothered to
come again, after last time.

470
00:36:41,640 --> 00:36:43,840
Why did you come back?

471
00:36:44,360 --> 00:36:47,640
And it wasn't because I
missed your sorry faces!

472
00:36:50,520 --> 00:36:52,750
You want to hear my story?

473
00:36:52,800 --> 00:36:56,310
I'm six years old, I'm sitting
on a bus together with my mother.

474
00:36:56,360 --> 00:36:58,360
It's the last stop.

475
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:02,440
My grandmother's house is the
last stop and it's a beautiful day.

476
00:37:03,680 --> 00:37:07,480
And my grandmother says to me,
"Boy, go and swim in the lake."

477
00:37:09,080 --> 00:37:11,820
And I swim and I swim and I swim.

478
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:16,200
And when I come back, my mother is gone.

479
00:37:17,400 --> 00:37:20,670
Has got back on that bus and driven away.

480
00:37:20,720 --> 00:37:23,990
And I don't see her again for eight years.

481
00:37:24,040 --> 00:37:25,990
Eight years.

482
00:37:26,040 --> 00:37:30,510
And when I do see her again,
I am 14 and she's stoned.

483
00:37:30,560 --> 00:37:32,710
And we have nothing to say.

484
00:37:32,760 --> 00:37:35,230
What would you like to say?

485
00:37:43,600 --> 00:37:47,400
All of the things you want to say
to someone who suddenly went away.

486
00:37:48,480 --> 00:37:50,420
How you miss them.

487
00:37:54,320 --> 00:37:57,800
How the air was sucked out of
your lungs the moment they left.

488
00:38:00,120 --> 00:38:02,590
How you will never, ever...

489
00:38:03,480 --> 00:38:06,480
.. fully inhale again in the same way.

490
00:38:10,680 --> 00:38:12,620
How you miss them.

491
00:38:13,280 --> 00:38:16,380
How you miss them till your teeth ache.

492
00:38:33,840 --> 00:38:35,470
Thank you.

493
00:38:38,840 --> 00:38:40,750
Yes, thank you, River.

494
00:38:40,800 --> 00:38:44,600
I-I was almost moved for a
moment, there, my friend.

495
00:38:45,480 --> 00:38:47,080
Poor River.

496
00:38:47,880 --> 00:38:49,560
(All alone.)

497
00:38:50,760 --> 00:38:54,320
Why don't you tell them about the
day you thought you were Rasputin?

498
00:39:01,480 --> 00:39:03,950
You have made your own hell, River.

499
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:06,550
You have bowed down to despair.

500
00:39:06,600 --> 00:39:09,190
All I have ever done is
shown you that those who feel

501
00:39:09,240 --> 00:39:11,980
capacity for love also feel hate!

502
00:39:13,080 --> 00:39:15,830
FEEL HATE, RIVER!

503
00:39:15,880 --> 00:39:18,620
UNTIL DEATH IS YOUR ONLY ESCAPE!

504
00:39:20,520 --> 00:39:23,620
No matter. The mind is its own place...

505
00:39:24,040 --> 00:39:28,150
.. and, in itself, can
make a heaven of hell.

506
00:39:28,200 --> 00:39:29,790
I'm your hell.

507
00:39:29,840 --> 00:39:32,040
I will never leave you.

508
00:39:33,920 --> 00:39:35,910
I'm not listening to you any more.

509
00:39:35,960 --> 00:39:37,900
I'M NOT LISTENING!

510
00:40:02,440 --> 00:40:03,980
I'm sorry.

511
00:40:51,440 --> 00:40:54,680
When I was 14, I was riding
buses and buying records.

512
00:40:57,960 --> 00:41:00,030
You weren't to know.

513
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:04,100
- You were...
- Because I didn't tell you.

514
00:41:12,280 --> 00:41:14,280
Where we're from...

515
00:41:15,440 --> 00:41:17,670
.. where we come from, that...

516
00:41:17,720 --> 00:41:19,920
doesn't make us, River.

517
00:41:21,880 --> 00:41:24,080
It can't be all we are.

518
00:41:31,680 --> 00:41:34,550
I don't know what you want from me.

519
00:42:15,200 --> 00:42:17,940
I've put on another three pounds.

520
00:42:22,560 --> 00:42:24,550
- I know.
- Right!

521
00:42:24,600 --> 00:42:27,000
I know the truth, Frankie.

522
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:38,400
I, uh...

523
00:42:39,560 --> 00:42:43,470
I passed this bloke I went
to school with yesterday.

